Headlines.Author: Daniel Hausmann
Headlines.Headline: Medical-Waste Firm Stericycle To Pay $245M For Smaller Rival

#text: (Updates with analyst comment on acquisition.) Medical-waste company Stericycle Inc.

said it has agreed to buy a smaller rival, Healthcare Waste Solutions Inc., for about $245 million in cash. The deal pairs up the number one and number two companies in the space, according to an analyst. Officials from both businesses as well as Altaris Capital weren't available for comment. Healthcare Waste Solutions, owned by health-care-focused investment firm Altaris Capital Partners LLC, has more than 20,000 customers, while Stericycle serves more than 280,000 businesses--including hospitals and blood banks--in North America.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Medical-Waste Firm Stericycle To Pay $245M For Smaller Rival

Headlines.Headline: Stericycle Records $5.4M Expense For Arbitration Settlement

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Stericycle Inc.

said Thursday that it recognized a pre-tax expense of $5.4 million in connection with a settlement of arbitration proceedings with Daniels Corp. The proceedings, initiated in February 2007, related to claims by Daniels that Stericycle's U.K. subsidiary, White Rose Environmental Ltd., had breached obligations that it owed to a joint venture it had formed with Daniels for the sale of Daniels reusable sharps containers.

Headlines.Author: Monica M. Clark
Headlines.Headline: Stericycle 1Q Net Climbs 7.7%, Revenue Jumps 21%

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Streicycle Inc.'s

first-quarter net income rose 7.7%, as a revenue boost from recent acquisitions helped offset a settlement charge. The Lake Forest, Ill., medical waste management company's earnings climbed to $31.7 million, or 35 cents a share, from $29.4 million, or 32 cents a share, a year earlier. Excluding items, per-share earnings were 39 cents. Revenue jumped 21% to $254.8 million from $211 million a year ago.

In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the medical waste management company said the notes have an interest rate of 5.64% and mature in 2015. The Lake Forest, Ill. company used the proceeds to reduce its borrowings under its revolving credit facility, the filing said.

Headlines.Headline: Stericycle Awarded $8.2M From SteriCorp

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Stericycle Inc.

said an arbitrator ruling in its dispute with SteriCorp Ltd. of Melbourne, Australia, awarded Stericyle $8.2 million for payments due under certain convertible notes. The Lake Forest, Ill., medical waste management company said the arbitrator awarded SteriCorp $14.5 million for its claim that Stericycle failed to supply SteriCorp with equipment conforming to specifications under an equipment supply agreement.

Headlines.Headline: Stericycle 3Q EPS 37c Vs EPS 30c

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Stericycle Inc.'s

third-quarter net income rose 19% to $32.9 million, or 37 cents a share, from $27.5 million, or 30 cents a share, a year earlier. The Lake Forest, Ill., waste management company's revenue increased 17% to $237.3 million from $203.3 million a year ago. On average, analysts polled by Thomson Financial predicted third-quarter earnings of 36 cents a share and revenue of $227 million.

#text: After the market closed, Kenneth Cole

reported in-line earnings for the fourth quarter but warned of a shortfall for fiscal 2001. The company posted fourth-quarter earnings of 52 cents a share. However, the company said that due to an increasingly difficult retail environment, earnings for fiscal 2001 would be about $1.85 a share. Analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial expect a profit of $2.17 a share. Shares closed down $1.75 to $31.25 ahead of the news.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Nike, Sawtek, Harris Corp. and more

#text: Nike

warned investors after the market closed Monday that it was lowering third quarter earnings estimates due to weak footwear sales in the U.S. For the third quarter, Nike said it expects to earn between 34 to 38 cents a share, well below Wall Street estimates of 53 cents a share. Nike reaffirmed its fourth quarter projections to come in at 60 to 65 cents a share, in line with estimates. Nike shares closed up 35 cents at $49.17 ahead of the news.

#text: Movado Group

shares plunged 37 percent
            Wednesday after the company warned that it will incur a net loss of $2.8 million to
            $3.2 million, or 21 to 25 cents a share, in the fourth quarter. The quarterly loss
            excludes a pre-tax one-time charge. In the comparable quarter of 1999, the watch maker
            made $5.4 million, or 41 cents. Full-year earnings are also seen below analysts?
            expectations. Movado blamed the expected shortfall on high expenses and
            lower-than-expected gross margins due to closeout sales and one-time charges. The stock
            fell 6 1/2 to close at 10 13/16.
